article.description: The Phoenix Suns held on to beat the Seattle SuperSonics 92-91 in overtime Tuesday night.
article.headline: Marion gets the dunk for win
article.linkText: Missed free throws cost Sonics in loss to Suns
article.story: PHOENIX (AP) -- For Phoenix coach Mike D'Antoni, it was a no-brainer to call for an alley-oop to Shawn Marion with the game on the line. Penny Hardaway threw a 30-foot inbounds pass over the rim, and Marion dunked with 5.6 seconds to go to lift the Suns to a 92-91 overtime win over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night. "Penny made an unbelievable pass to Matrix," D'Antoni. "Only those two guys could do it, and it helped us get the big win that we needed." The Suns snapped a six-game losing streak to win for the first time in four games under D'Antoni. "Everybody wanted to get a win," Stephon Marbury said. "We wanted to win for coach, and he wanted to win for us." Marion had 19 points and 14 rebounds, Hardaway had 18 points and Marbury scored 17. After Marion scored over Seattle's Vladimir Radmanovic, Antonio Daniels tried to get the ball to Rashard Lewis, but the sore-shouldered Sonics forward lost the ball out of bounds with 1.8 seconds left. Marion then went to the free throw line, missing the first shot and purposely missing the second. Brent Barry came down with the rebound, but the buzzer went off as his pass crossed midcourt. "I'm glad we won an ugly game," Hardaway said about an overtime in which the teams combined for just five points. "We really needed it, because we're going to Portland, and it takes some pressure off of us because we got that win. Now we can go up there and have fun and play hard, because we're getting better every game." Lewis had 27 points and 13 rebounds, but missed two free throws with 7.1 seconds left that could have sent it to a second overtime. Seattle led 91-90 at the time. Radmanovic had 16 points and 14 rebounds, and Daniels scored 18 and had 10 rebounds, giving the Sonics a 59-41 edge. That was offset by Seattle's turnovers -- 26 to the Suns' 13. "One thing we talked about before the game: (Phoenix) is a good team at turning turnovers into points," Daniels said. "They do a good job of getting into the passing lane, and once you turn it over they make you pay." The Sonics had two chances to end it in the final 28.5 seconds of regulation, but Ansu Sesay made only one of two free throws to tie it at 89. Marbury drove past Radmanovic as the clock ticked down, but missed a scoop layup and Sesay got the rebound. After a Seattle timeout with 3.5 seconds to go, Barry missed a jumper. Lewis, who strained his left shoulder Sunday against Milwaukee, skipped practice Monday but decided to play after doctors assured him it posed little danger of further injury. The team's scoring leader, who had a career-high 50 points against the Los Angeles Clippers in Japan on Oct. 31, was 10-for-25 from the field and played 45 minutes. Daniels had eight points in the first four minutes, and the Sonics opened a 17-6 lead with 6:43 left in the first quarter when Lewis made an 18-foot baseline jumper and a 3-pointer 35 seconds apart. Marion and Marbury had six points each while the Suns rallied to 22-18, but in the final 57 seconds of the quarter Radmanovic sank two 3-pointers and passed to Barry for a layup that made it 30-18. The Suns fell behind by 16 in the second quarter, but then made a 20-2 run capped by Hardaway's jumper for a 38-36 lead with 1:22 remaining. No more than five points separated the teams after that. "We had some looks that we didn't knock down," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "Had some free throws we didn't knock down. Twenty-six turnovers? I don't even know how we stayed in this game." Game Notes: Suns C Scott Williams sprained his right knee after playing 10 minutes in the first half and did not return. ... Both teams were among the bottom eight in scoring by opponents coming in, the Suns allowing 96.0 points a game to Seattle's 96.1. ... D'Antoni took over for the fired Frank Johnson on Dec. 10. ... The Sonics have lost five of six road games after starting 4-1 away from home. ... D'Antoni talked this week about playing a big lineup, but started small -- with three guards -- for the seventh straight game since Amare Stoudemire sprained his ankle Dec. 5 at Boston.
